      <h2 class="section-title">What Is Clean Code?</h2>
      <div class="accent-bar" style="background:linear-gradient(90deg,var(--accent1),transparent)"></div>
    </div>

    <div class="cards-grid">
      <div class="card purple">
        <div class="card-icon">🧹</div>
        <div class="card-title">Clean Code</div>
        <div class="card-body"><strong>Readable, maintainable, extendable.</strong> Other developers can read it, understand it, and build on it without asking you questions.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="card cyan">
        <div class="card-icon">⚙️</div>
        <div class="card-title">Working Code</div>
        <div class="card-body"><strong>Does what it is supposed to do.</strong> Correct logic, passes tests — but doesn't have to be pretty.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="card green">
        <div class="card-icon">✅</div>
        <div class="card-title">Good Code</div>
        <div class="card-body"><strong>Clean + Working.</strong> This is what you must always aim for. The intersection of both circles.</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="highlight-box amber" style="margin-top:1.5rem">
      <div class="hb-title">⚡ The WTF Metric</div>
      <p>Code quality is measured in <strong>WTF/minute</strong> (Works That Frustrate per minute). The goal is to reduce WTF/minute to zero. You do this by: letting others review code, standardizing style, and practicing constantly.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="highlight-box cyan" style="margin-top:1rem">
      <div class="hb-title">📖 Why Readability Matters</div>
      <ul>
        <li>When changing code: Find component → Find affected lines → Write → Test</li>
        <li><strong>Readable code saves time</strong> at every step of this process</li>
        <li>It also <strong>improves maintenance</strong> and <strong>increases extendibility</strong></li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

