  <!-- SECTION 1: MEANINGFUL NAMES -->
  <section class="section" id="names">
    <div class="section-header">
      <span class="section-num">01</span>
      <h2 class="section-title">13 Rules: Meaningful Names</h2>
      <div class="accent-bar" style="background:linear-gradient(90deg,var(--accent1),transparent)"></div>
    </div>

    <div class="memory-box">
      <div class="mb-title">🧠 Memory Trick — The 13 Rules Acronym</div>
      <div class="mb-trick">UI · AD · MD · EN · US · CN · MN · AE · UP · AM · DC · PP · MC</div>
      <div class="mb-expand"><strong>U</strong>se Intention · <strong>A</strong>void Disinformation · <strong>M</strong>eaningful Distinctions · <strong>E</strong>liminate Noise · <strong>U</strong>se Searchable · <strong>C</strong>lass Names · <strong>M</strong>ethod Names · <strong>A</strong>void Encodings · <strong>U</strong>se Pronounceable · <strong>A</strong>void Mental Mapping · <strong>D</strong>on't Be Cute · <strong>P</strong>ick One Word · <strong>A</strong>dd Context</div>
    </div>

    <!-- RULE 1 -->
    <div class="big-rule">
      <div class="big-rule-num">01</div>
      <div class="big-rule-title">
        <span class="tag purple">RULE 1</span>
        Use Intention-Revealing Names
      </div>
      <p>The name of a variable, function, or class should answer: <strong>why it exists</strong>, <strong>what it does</strong>, <strong>how it is used</strong>. If a name requires a comment → the name fails. Choosing good names takes time but saves more than it takes.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="compare">
      <div class="compare-box">
        <div class="compare-label bad">❌ Bad – Implicit</div>
        <pre>public List&lt;int[]&gt; getThem() {
  List&lt;int[]&gt; list1 = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();
  for (int[] x : theList) {
    if (x[0] == 4)
      list1.add(x);
  }
  return list1;
}</pre>
      </div>
      <div class="compare-box">
        <div class="compare-label good">✅ Good – Explicit</div>
        <pre>public List&lt;Cell&gt; getFlaggedCells() {
  List&lt;Cell&gt; flaggedCells = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();
  for (Cell cell : gameBoard) {
    if (cell.isFlagged())
      flaggedCells.add(cell);
  }
  return flaggedCells;
}</pre>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="highlight-box green">
      <div class="hb-title">Key Improvements Made</div>
      <ul>
        <li><code>theList</code> → <code>gameBoard</code></li>
        <li><code>x[0] == 4</code> → <code>cell.isFlagged()</code> (hides magic numbers)</li>
        <li><code>getThem()</code> → <code>getFlaggedCells()</code></li>
        <li><code>int[]</code> → <code>Cell</code> class (intention-revealing type)</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <!-- RULE 2 -->
    <div class="big-rule" style="margin-top:2rem">
      <div class="big-rule-num">02</div>
      <div class="big-rule-title">
        <span class="tag red">RULE 2</span>
        Avoid Disinformation
      </div>
      <p>Never leave <strong>false clues</strong> that mislead. Avoid keywords, ambiguous words, inconsistent spellings, and confusingly similar names. Beware of names that vary only in small ways.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="compare">
      <div class="compare-box">
        <div class="compare-label bad">❌ Confusingly similar</div>
        <pre>XYZControllerForEfficientHandlingOfStrings
XYZControllerForEfficientStorageOfStrings</pre>
      </div>
      <div class="compare-box">
        <div class="compare-label bad">❌ l vs 1 vs O vs 0</div>
        <pre>int a = l;
if (O == l) {
  a = O1;
} else {
  l = 01;
}</pre>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="highlight-box red">
      <div class="hb-title">⚠️ Never use l (lowercase L) or O (uppercase O) as variable names</div>
      <p>They look like the numbers <strong>1</strong> and <strong>0</strong>. Changing the font to "fix" this is a <strong>DIRTY HACK</strong> — rename instead.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- RULE 3 -->
    <div class="big-rule" style="margin-top:2rem">
      <div class="big-rule-num">03</div>
      <div class="big-rule-title">
        <span class="tag cyan">RULE 3</span>
        Use Meaningful Distinctions
      </div>
      <p>If names must be different, they should <strong>mean something different</strong>. Number-series names (<code>a1, a2, aN</code>) are <strong>non-informative</strong>. Noise words like <code>Data</code>, <code>Info</code>, <code>The</code> add nothing.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="compare">
      <div class="compare-box">
        <div class="compare-label bad">❌ Non-informative numbers</div>
        <pre>void copyChars(char a1[], char a2[]) {
  for (int i = 0; i &lt;= a1.length; i++)
    a2[i] = a1[i];
}</pre>
      </div>
      <div class="compare-box">
        <div class="compare-label good">✅ Meaningful names</div>
        <pre>void copyChars(char source[], char destination[]) {
  for (int i = 0; i &lt;= source.length; i++)
    destination[i] = source[i];
}</pre>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- RULE 4 -->
    <div class="big-rule" style="margin-top:2rem">
      <div class="big-rule-num">04</div>
      <div class="big-rule-title">
        <span class="tag amber">RULE 4</span>
        Eliminate Noise Words
      </div>
      <p>Noise words are <strong>redundant</strong>. The word <code>variable</code> should never appear in a variable name. The word <code>table</code> should never appear in a table name. How is <code>NameString</code> better than <code>Name</code>? It isn't.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="cards-grid">
      <div class="card red">
        <div class="card-title">❌ Noisy / Redundant</div>
        <div class="card-body">
          <code>customerObject</code><br>
          <code>accountData</code><br>
          <code>theCustomer</code><br>
          <code>NameString</code><br>
          <code>moneyAmount</code>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="card green">
        <div class="card-title">✅ Clean / Noise-Free</div>
        <div class="card-body">
          <code>customer</code><br>
          <code>account</code><br>
          <code>customer</code><br>
          <code>Name</code><br>
          <code>money</code>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- RULE 5 -->
    <div class="big-rule" style="margin-top:2rem">
      <div class="big-rule-num">05</div>
      <div class="big-rule-title">
        <span class="tag green">RULE 5</span>
        Use Searchable Names
      </div>
      <p>Single-letter names and numeric constants are <strong>impossible to search</strong> in a codebase. If used in multiple places, give it a search-friendly name. <strong>The length of a name should correspond to the size of its scope.</strong> Single letters are ONLY allowed as local loop variables in short methods.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="compare">
      <div class="compare-box">
        <div class="compare-label bad">❌ Can't search for 7</div>
        <pre>for (int j=0; j&lt;7; j++) {
  s += t[j];
}</pre>
      </div>
      <div class="compare-box">
        <div class="compare-label good">✅ Search for NUMBER_OF_SUBJECTS</div>
        <pre>int NUMBER_OF_SUBJECTS = 7;
int totalGrade = 0;
for (int j=0; j &lt; NUMBER_OF_SUBJECTS; j++) {
  totalGrade += studentGrade[j];
}</pre>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- RULE 6 & 7 -->
    <div class="cards-grid" style="margin-top:2rem">
      <div class="card purple">
        <div class="card-icon">🏛️</div>
        <div class="card-title"><span class="rule-num">R6</span> Class Names</div>
        <div class="card-body">
          Answer <strong>"WHO?"</strong><br>
          Use <strong>noun or noun phrase</strong>: <code>Customer</code>, <code>WikiPage</code>, <code>Account</code>, <code>AddressParser</code><br>
          <strong>Avoid:</strong> <code>Manager</code>, <code>Processor</code>, <code>Data</code>, <code>Info</code><br>
          Class name should <strong>NEVER be a verb</strong>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="card cyan">
        <div class="card-icon">⚡</div>
        <div class="card-title"><span class="rule-num">R7</span> Method Names</div>
        <div class="card-body">
          Answer <strong>"WHAT DOES IT DO?"</strong><br>
          Use <strong>verb or verb phrase</strong>: <code>postPayment</code>, <code>deletePage</code>, <code>save</code><br>
          Overloaded constructors → use <strong>static factory methods</strong> with descriptive names
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="compare" style="margin-top:1rem">
      <div class="compare-box">
        <div class="compare-label bad">❌ Ambiguous constructors</div>
        <pre>Address a1 = new Address(1, "tahrir", "helwan");
Address a2 = new Address(1, 4, 4, "tahrir", "helwan", "cairo", "Egypt");</pre>
      </div>
      <div class="compare-box">
        <div class="compare-label good">✅ Static factory methods</div>
        <pre>Address short = Address.createShortAddress(1, "tahrir", "helwan");
Address full  = Address.createFullAddress(1, 4, 4, "tahrir", "helwan", "cairo", "Egypt");</pre>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- RULE 8 -->
    <div class="big-rule" style="margin-top:2rem">
      <div class="big-rule-num">08</div>
      <div class="big-rule-title">
        <span class="tag red">RULE 8</span>
        Avoid Encodings (Hungarian Notation)
      </div>
      <p>Hungarian Notation (e.g., <code>iAge</code>, <code>strName</code>, <code>lTotal</code>) adds type prefixes to names. <strong>Microsoft itself said "DO NOT use Hungarian notation" since 2008.</strong> Problems: when you change the type, you must rename; it makes code noisier; it confuses readers.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="highlight-box amber">
      <div class="hb-title">Hungarian Notation — Know it to Avoid it</div>
      <ul>
        <li>Invented by Charles Simonyi at Microsoft</li>
        <li><strong>Example:</strong> <code>int iAge</code>, <code>String strName</code>, <code>long lTotal</code></li>
        <li>Was useful in weakly-typed languages (PHP), but <strong>useless in Java/C#/modern languages</strong></li>
        <li><strong>Interfaces:</strong> Prefer <code>ShapeFactory</code> over <code>IShapeFactory</code>. If encoding is needed, encode the implementation: <code>ShapeFactoryImp</code> or <code>CShapeFactory</code></li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <!-- RULE 9 -->
    <div class="big-rule" style="margin-top:2rem">
      <div class="big-rule-num">09</div>
      <div class="big-rule-title">
        <span class="tag cyan">RULE 9</span>
        Use Pronounceable Names
      </div>
      <p>If you can't pronounce it, you can't discuss it without sounding ridiculous. <strong>Programming is a social activity.</strong></p>
    </div>

    <div class="compare">
      <div class="compare-box">
        <div class="compare-label bad">❌ Unpronounceable</div>
        <pre>class DtaRcrd102 {
  private Date genymdhms;
  private Date modymdhms;
  private final String pszqint = "102";
}</pre>
      </div>
      <div class="compare-box">
        <div class="compare-label good">✅ Pronounceable</div>
        <pre>class Customer {
  private Date generationTimestamp;
  private Date modificationTimestamp;
  private final String recordId = "102";
}</pre>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- RULE 10 -->
    <div class="big-rule" style="margin-top:2rem">
      <div class="big-rule-num">10</div>
      <div class="big-rule-title">
        <span class="tag amber">RULE 10</span>
        Avoid Mental Mapping
      </div>
      <p>Readers shouldn't have to mentally translate your names. Don't use single letters for domain concepts. Exception: <code>i</code>, <code>j</code>, <code>k</code> for loop counters are universally understood and acceptable.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- RULE 11 -->
    <div class="big-rule" style="margin-top:2rem">
      <div class="big-rule-num">11</div>
      <div class="big-rule-title">
        <span class="tag green">RULE 11</span>
        Don't Be Cute
      </div>
      <p>Clever jokes only work for people who share your humor — and only while they remember the joke. <strong>Say what you mean. Mean what you say.</strong></p>
    </div>

    <div class="cards-grid">
      <div class="card red">
        <div class="card-title">❌ "Cute" Names</div>
        <div class="card-body"><code>whack()</code> → actually kills a process<br><code>eatMyShorts()</code> → actually aborts</div>
      </div>
      <div class="card green">
        <div class="card-title">✅ Honest Names</div>
        <div class="card-body"><code>kill()</code><br><code>abort()</code></div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- RULE 12 -->
    <div class="big-rule" style="margin-top:2rem">
      <div class="big-rule-num">12</div>
      <div class="big-rule-title">
        <span class="tag purple">RULE 12</span>
        Pick One Word Per Concept
      </div>
      <p>Pick one word for one abstract concept and <strong>stick with it</strong> everywhere. A <strong>consistent lexicon</strong> is a huge boon to developers using your code.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="compare">
      <div class="compare-box">
        <div class="compare-label bad">❌ Inconsistent synonyms</div>
        <pre>getArticles()     // class A
fetchUsers()      // class B
retrievePages()   // class C</pre>
      </div>
      <div class="compare-box">
        <div class="compare-label good">✅ One word: get</div>
        <pre>getArticles()   // class A
getUsers()      // class B
getPages()      // class C</pre>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- RULE 13 -->
    <div class="big-rule" style="margin-top:2rem">
      <div class="big-rule-num">13</div>
      <div class="big-rule-title">
        <span class="tag cyan">RULE 13</span>
        Add Meaningful Context
      </div>
      <p>A variable <code>state</code> alone is unclear — it could be app state, UI state, US state... But <code>addrState</code> alongside <code>addrFirstName</code>, <code>addrLastName</code>, <code>addrCity</code> is immediately understood as part of an address.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="highlight-box purple">
      <div class="hb-title">Context Strategy</div>
      <ul>
        <li>Use <strong>prefixes</strong>: <code>addrFirstName</code>, <code>addrLastName</code>, <code>addrState</code></li>
        <li>Better: <strong>encapsulate in a class</strong> called <code>Address</code></li>
        <li>Also: <strong>Use Solution Domain Names</strong> (CS terms, patterns, algorithms) when applicable</li>
        <li>Use <strong>Problem Domain Names</strong> when the code is more about business logic</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="divider"></div>

  <!-- SECTION 2: FUNCTIONS -->
  <section class="section" id="functions">
    <div class="section-header">
      <span class="section-num">02</span>
      <h2 class="section-title">Functions</h2>
      <div class="accent-bar" style="background:linear-gradient(90deg,var(--accent2),transparent)"></div>
    </div>

    <div class="highlight-box cyan">
      <div class="hb-title">🔑 The Golden Rule</div>
      <p><strong>The first rule of functions: they should be SMALL.</strong><br>
      <strong>The second rule: they should be SMALLER than that.</strong><br>
      Any method longer than ~10 lines should make you ask questions. Use "Extract Method" to reduce length.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- Function Rule 1 -->
    <div class="big-rule" style="margin-top:2rem">
      <div class="big-rule-num">F1</div>
      <div class="big-rule-title">
        <span class="tag cyan">RULE F1</span>
        Do One Thing (Single Responsibility)
      </div>
      <p><strong>Functions should do one thing. They should do it well. They should do it only.</strong><br>
      If a function does only one thing, it will naturally be small. How to check: if you can <strong>extract another function with a different name from it</strong> — it's doing more than one thing.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="wide-card">
      <div class="wc-title">📖 Refactoring Example: Long → Single-Purpose</div>
      <div class="compare">
        <div class="compare-box">
          <div class="compare-label bad">❌ Does everything in one method</div>
          <pre>void addDataToFile(String path, Person p) {
  // reads file
  FileInputStream readData = new FileInputStream(path);
  ObjectInputStream readStream = new ObjectInputStream(readData);
  ArrayList people = (ArrayList) readStream.readObject();
  readStream.close();
  // adds
  people.add(p);
  // writes
  FileOutputStream writeData = new FileOutputStream(path);
  ObjectOutputStream writeStream = new ObjectOutputStream(writeData);
  writeStream.writeObject(people);
  writeStream.flush();
  writeStream.close();
  // prints
  System.out.println(people.toString());
}</pre>
        </div>
        <div class="compare-box">
          <div class="compare-label good">✅ Extracted single-purpose methods</div>
          <pre>// Each method does ONE thing:

ArrayList readDataFromFile(String path) { ... }

ArrayList addDataToList(Person p, ArrayList people) {
  people.add(p);
  return people;
}

void addDataToFile(String path, ArrayList people) {
  writeDataToFile(path, people);
}

void printPersonDataFile(ArrayList people) {
  System.out.println(people.toString());
}

// Called from main:
ArrayList people = readDataFromFile(filePath);
addDataToList(p, people);
addDataToFile(filePath, people);
printPersonDataFile(readDataFromFile(filePath));</pre>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Function Rule 2 -->
    <div class="big-rule" style="margin-top:2rem">
      <div class="big-rule-num">F2</div>
      <div class="big-rule-title">
        <span class="tag purple">RULE F2</span>
        One Level of Abstraction (SLAP)
      </div>
      <p><strong>Single Level of Abstraction Principle.</strong> All statements within a function must be at the <strong>same level of abstraction</strong>. Mixing high-level calls with low-level implementation details in one function is confusing.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="compare">
      <div class="compare-box">
        <div class="compare-label bad">❌ Mixed abstraction levels</div>
        <pre>void printNumbers1To35() {
  printNumbersOneToTen(); // HIGH level
  for(int i=11; i&lt;21; i++)  // LOW level
    System.out.println(i);
  System.out.println(21); // LOW level
  // ... nested mess
}</pre>
      </div>
      <div class="compare-box">
        <div class="compare-label good">✅ Same abstraction level</div>
        <pre>void printNumbers1To35() {
  printNumbersOneToTen();
  printNumbersElevenToTwenty();
  printNumberTwentyOne();
  printNumbersTwentyTwoToThirtyFive();
}
// All calls are at the SAME level ✓</pre>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Function Rule 3 -->
    <div class="big-rule" style="margin-top:2rem">
      <div class="big-rule-num">F3</div>
      <div class="big-rule-title">
        <span class="tag amber">RULE F3</span>
        The Fewer Arguments, The Better
      </div>
      <p>Arguments are troublesome and harder to understand. Ideal: <strong>0 arguments (niladic)</strong>. Then 1 (monadic). Then 2 (dyadic). <strong>Avoid 3+ arguments</strong>. <strong>Never use 4+ arguments.</strong></p>
    </div>

    <div class="rules-list">
      <div class="rule-item">
        <div class="rule-bullet" style="background:rgba(16,185,129,0.2);color:#6ee7b7">0</div>
        <p><strong>Niladic</strong> — Zero arguments. Best. Can move the output to a class field.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="rule-item">
        <div class="rule-bullet" style="background:rgba(6,182,212,0.2);color:#67e8f9">1</div>
        <p><strong>Monadic</strong> — One argument. Good. e.g., <code>writeText(text)</code></p>
      </div>
      <div class="rule-item">
        <div class="rule-bullet" style="background:rgba(245,158,11,0.2);color:#fcd34d">2</div>
        <p><strong>Dyadic</strong> — Two arguments. Acceptable but try to avoid. e.g., <code>writeText(stream, text)</code> → move stream to class field</p>
      </div>
      <div class="rule-item">
        <div class="rule-bullet" style="background:rgba(239,68,68,0.2);color:#fca5a5">3+</div>
        <p><strong>Triadic+</strong> — Avoid completely. Instead, <strong>group arguments into an object</strong>: <code>sendRequest(Request request)</code> instead of <code>sendRequest(ip, port, user, password, body)</code></p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Function Rule 4: Flag Arguments -->
    <div class="big-rule" style="margin-top:2rem">
      <div class="big-rule-num">F4</div>
      <div class="big-rule-title">
        <span class="tag red">RULE F4</span>
        Never Use Flag Arguments (Boolean params)
      </div>
      <p>Passing a boolean into a function is <strong>terrible practice</strong>. It screams that the function does <strong>more than one thing</strong>. Split the method into two.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="compare">
      <div class="compare-box">
        <div class="compare-label bad">❌ Flag argument = 2 functions in 1</div>
        <pre>void printAddress(boolean longFormat) {
  if (longFormat)
    // print long address
  else
    // print short address
}</pre>
      </div>
      <div class="compare-box">
        <div class="compare-label good">✅ Two honest methods</div>
        <pre>void printShortAddress() {
  // print short address
}

void printLongAddress() {
  // print long address
}</pre>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Function Rule 5: Keep Blocks Small -->
    <div class="big-rule" style="margin-top:2rem">
      <div class="big-rule-num">F5</div>
      <div class="big-rule-title">
        <span class="tag green">RULE F5</span>
        Keep Blocks Small — One Indent Level
      </div>
      <p>Blocks inside <code>if</code>, <code>else</code>, <code>while</code> should be <strong>one line long</strong> — ideally a function call. Functions should have an <strong>indent level of no more than 1 or 2</strong>. No deep nesting.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- Function Rule 6: Replace Conditional with Polymorphism -->
    <div class="big-rule" style="margin-top:2rem">
      <div class="big-rule-num">F6</div>
      <div class="big-rule-title">
        <span class="tag purple">RULE F6</span>
        Replace Conditional With Polymorphism
      </div>
      <p>If/switch statements based on type <strong>violate the Open/Closed Principle</strong> — to add a new type you must modify existing code. And the same switch is likely duplicated in many places. <strong>Use polymorphism instead.</strong></p>
    </div>

    <div class="wide-card">
      <div class="wc-title">📖 Parking Example: Switch → Polymorphism</div>
      <div class="compare">
        <div class="compare-box">
          <div class="compare-label bad">❌ Switch nightmare (violates OCP)</div>
          <pre>public ParkingSpotSize spaceRequired() {
  switch (type) {
    case BICYCLE: return SMALL;
    case BIKE:    return MEDIUM;
    case CAR:     return LARGE;
    case BUS:     return XL;
  }
}
public BigDecimal parkingCharges() {
  switch (type) {
    case BICYCLE: return 10.00;
    case BIKE:    return 20.00;
    case CAR:     return 50.00;
    case BUS:     return 100.00;
  }
}</pre>
        </div>
        <div class="compare-box">
          <div class="compare-label good">✅ Polymorphism (follows OCP)</div>
          <pre>public interface Vehicle {
  ParkingSpotSize spaceRequired();
  BigDecimal parkingCharges();
}

public class Car implements Vehicle {
  public ParkingSpotSize spaceRequired() {
    return LARGE;
  }
  public BigDecimal parkingCharges() {
    return BigDecimal.valueOf(50.00);
  }
}
// Add new types without changing existing code!</pre>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="highlight-box red">
      <div class="hb-title">Why the switch version is bad</div>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Hard to read</strong> — many conditionals everywhere</li>
        <li><strong>Violates Open/Closed Principle</strong> — adding a new vehicle type requires modifying all switch statements</li>
        <li><strong>Violates Do One Thing</strong> — handles all types in one class</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="divider"></div>

  <!-- SECTION 3: OBJECTS & DATA STRUCTURES -->
  <section class="section" id="objects">
    <div class="section-header">
      <span class="section-num">03</span>
      <h2 class="section-title">Objects &amp; Data Structures</h2>
      <div class="accent-bar" style="background:linear-gradient(90deg,var(--accent4),transparent)"></div>
    </div>

    <!-- Data Abstraction -->
    <div class="big-rule">
      <div class="big-rule-num">O1</div>
      <div class="big-rule-title">
        <span class="tag green">RULE O1</span>
        Data Abstraction
      </div>
      <p>Abstraction means <strong>hiding implementation</strong>. It does NOT mean making variables private then adding getters/setters that expose them directly. It means providing <strong>abstract interfaces</strong> that let users manipulate data without knowing the implementation details.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="compare">
      <div class="compare-box">
        <div class="compare-label bad">❌ Not abstraction — just accessors</div>
        <pre>// This is NOT abstraction!
// These methods reveal internal structure:
double getFuelTankCapacityInGallons();
double getGallonsOfGasoline();</pre>
      </div>
      <div class="compare-box">
        <div class="compare-label good">✅ True abstraction</div>
        <pre>// User sees percentage, NOT gallons
// Internal implementation is hidden:
double getPercentFuelRemaining();</pre>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Data/Object Anti-Symmetry -->
    <div class="big-rule" style="margin-top:2rem">
      <div class="big-rule-num">O2</div>
      <div class="big-rule-title">
        <span class="tag purple">RULE O2</span>
        Data/Object Anti-Symmetry
      </div>
      <p>Objects and Data Structures are <strong>opposites</strong> in design. Understanding this trade-off is crucial.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="law-grid">
      <div class="law-box">
        <h4>📦 Data Structures (Procedural)</h4>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Expose</strong> their data (public fields)</li>
          <li><strong>No behavior/functions</strong> of their own</li>
          <li>✅ Easy to <strong>add new functions</strong> (add to Geometry class)</li>
          <li>❌ Hard to <strong>add new data types</strong> (must update all functions)</li>
          <li><strong>Use when:</strong> adding new functions more often than data types</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="law-box">
        <h4>🏛️ Objects (OO)</h4>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Hide</strong> their data (private fields)</li>
          <li><strong>Expose behavior</strong> through methods</li>
          <li>✅ Easy to <strong>add new classes</strong> (no existing functions affected)</li>
          <li>❌ Hard to <strong>add new functions</strong> (all classes must implement it)</li>
          <li><strong>Use when:</strong> adding new data types more often than functions</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="highlight-box amber">
      <div class="hb-title">⚡ The Key Insight — Anti-Symmetry</div>
      <p><strong>What's easy for OO is hard for Procedural, and vice versa.</strong><br>
      In complex systems → prefer OO (you'll add more types).<br>
      For simple utilities → procedural can be fine (you'll add more functions).</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="divider"></div>

  <!-- SECTION 4: LAW OF DEMETER -->
  <section class="section" id="lod">
    <div class="section-header">
      <span class="section-num">04</span>
      <h2 class="section-title">Law of Demeter (LoD)</h2>
      <div class="accent-bar" style="background:linear-gradient(90deg,var(--accent6),transparent)"></div>
    </div>

    <div class="big-rule">
      <div class="big-rule-num">LoD</div>
      <div class="big-rule-title">
        <span class="tag pink" style="background:rgba(236,72,153,0.2);color:#f9a8d4;border:1px solid rgba(236,72,153,0.3)">RULE LoD</span>
        Principle of Least Knowledge
      </div>
      <p>A module should <strong>not know about the inner details</strong> of objects it manipulates. A software component should not have knowledge of the internal workings of other objects. LoD is a specific case of <strong>loose coupling</strong>.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="highlight-box cyan">
      <div class="hb-title">The Two Mottos</div>
      <p style="font-size:1.1rem;font-weight:700;color:#67e8f9;margin-bottom:0.5rem">"Only talk to your immediate friends."</p>
      <p style="font-size:1.1rem;font-weight:700;color:#67e8f9">"Don't talk to strangers."</p>
    </div>

    <div class="big-rule" style="margin-top:2rem">
      <div class="big-rule-title">A method M of class C can only call methods of:</div>
      <div class="rules-list" style="margin-top:1rem">
        <div class="rule-item">
          <div class="rule-bullet" style="background:rgba(16,185,129,0.2);color:#6ee7b7">1</div>
          <p><strong>C itself</strong> — its own methods</p>
        </div>
        <div class="rule-item">
          <div class="rule-bullet" style="background:rgba(16,185,129,0.2);color:#6ee7b7">2</div>
          <p><strong>M's parameters</strong> — objects directly passed in</p>
        </div>
        <div class="rule-item">
          <div class="rule-bullet" style="background:rgba(16,185,129,0.2);color:#6ee7b7">3</div>
          <p><strong>Any objects created within M</strong> — objects you created yourself</p>
        </div>
        <div class="rule-item">
          <div class="rule-bullet" style="background:rgba(16,185,129,0.2);color:#6ee7b7">4</div>
          <p><strong>C's direct component objects</strong> — fields of the class</p>
        </div>
        <div class="rule-item">
          <div class="rule-bullet" style="background:rgba(16,185,129,0.2);color:#6ee7b7">5</div>
          <p><strong>Global variables</strong> accessible by C in scope of M (static fields in Java)</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="compare" style="margin-top:1.5rem">
      <div class="compare-box">
        <div class="compare-label bad">❌ Violates LoD — Train Wreck</div>
        <pre>// DON'T chain calls like this!
employee.getDepartment()
        .getManager()
        .approveExpense(expenses);

// Calling getOwner() is OK (it's a parameter)
// But calling .getAddress() then .getStreet()
// on what getOwner() returned is NOT OK!</pre>
      </div>
      <div class="compare-box">
        <div class="compare-label good">✅ Follows LoD</div>
        <pre>// Manager is injected via constructor
class Employee {
  private Manager manager;
  
  Employee(Manager manager) {
    this.manager = manager;
  }
  
  void submitExpense(Expenses expenses) {
    manager.approveExpense(expenses);
  }
}

// Call it cleanly:
Manager mgr = new Manager();
Employee emp = new Employee(mgr);
emp.submitExpense(expenses);</pre>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="highlight-box red">
      <div class="hb-title">⚠️ "Train Wreck" — The Most Common LoD Violation</div>
      <p><code>a.getB().getC().getD()</code> — chained method calls. Each <code>.get()</code> returns an unknown stranger, and you're talking to that stranger's stranger. This creates <strong>tight coupling</strong> — these classes cannot operate independently.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

